### What is Lazy Loading?

Lazy loading loads feature modules **on demand** rather than at initial application load. This reduces the initial bundle size and improves startup time.

### Lazy Loading with NgModules

Use `loadChildren` in routing configuration:

```typescript
const routes: Routes = [
  { path: '', component: HomeComponent },
  {
    path: 'products',
    loadChildren: () => import('./products/products.module').then(m => m.ProductsModule)
  },
  {
    path: 'admin',
    loadChildren: () => import('./admin/admin.module').then(m => m.AdminModule)
  }
];
```

The `ProductsModule` defines its own routes:

```typescript
@NgModule({
  imports: [
    RouterModule.forChild([
      { path: '', component: ProductListComponent },
      { path: ':id', component: ProductDetailComponent }
    ])
  ]
})
export class ProductsModule { }
```

### Lazy Loading with Standalone Components

Angular 14+ supports lazy loading standalone components directly without NgModules:

```typescript
const routes: Routes = [
  {
    path: 'products',
    loadComponent: () => import('./products/product-list.component').then(m => m.ProductListComponent)
  },
  {
    path: 'products/:id',
    loadComponent: () => import('./products/product-detail.component').then(m => m.ProductDetailComponent)
  }
];
```

### Preloading Strategies

After the initial bundle loads, you can preload lazy modules in the background:

```typescript
import { PreloadAllModules, NoPreloading } from '@angular/router';

// Preload all lazy modules after initial load
@NgModule({
  imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes, {
    preloadingStrategy: PreloadAllModules
  })]
})

// No preloading (default)
@NgModule({
  imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes, {
    preloadingStrategy: NoPreloading
  })]
})
```

### Custom Preloading Strategy

```typescript
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CustomPreloader implements PreloadingStrategy {
  preload(route: Route, load: () => Observable<any>): Observable<any> {
    // Only preload routes with `data: { preload: true }`
    return route.data?.['preload'] ? load() : of(null);
  }
}

// Usage in routes
{ path: 'dashboard', loadChildren: ..., data: { preload: true } }

// Apply
RouterModule.forRoot(routes, { preloadingStrategy: CustomPreloader })
```

### Build Output

With lazy loading, Angular CLI produces separate chunk files:
```
dist/
├── main.js          # Main bundle
├── polyfills.js     # Polyfills
├── styles.css       # Global styles
├── products-module.js  # Lazy chunk
└── admin-module.js     # Lazy chunk
```

### Benefits

- Faster initial load time
- Smaller initial bundle
- Code splitting without manual configuration
- Better performance on slow networks

